icken  .","Irish (Wexford): of English origin (see 1 and 2 above), taken to Ireland in the 17th century. When the Irish surname is not of English origin, it may be an Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Deocáin</b> ‘descendant of <i>Deocán</i>’, a personal name of uncertain etymology."],"variants":[{"name":"Dakan","meanings":["Probably an altered form of English   Deacon  .","Possibly of Dutch origin, see   Dakin  ."]},{"name":"Iacono","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Mario, Salvatore, Giovanni, Sal, Vito, Angelo, Carmine, Gaetano, Gennaro, Giuseppe, Silverio, Aniello, Antonio, Leonardo, Pacifico, Rodolfo, Rosario, Salvadore, Ubaldo.","Italian (southern):","from <i>iacono</i>, a southern dialect form of <i>diacono</i> ‘deacon’; see   Deacon  ."]},{"name":"Deakin","meanings":["variant of   Deacon  .","variant of   Dicken  .","English:"]},{"name":"Degon","meanings":["English (Devon): probably a variant of   Deacon  . This form of the surname has died out in England.","Indian (Punjab): Sikh name of unexplained etymology."]},{"name":"Dicken","meanings":["English (Staffordshire and Derbyshire): from the Middle English personal name <i>Dicun</i>, <i>Decoun</i>, a pet form of   Dick  . It was later altered to <i>Dickin</i>, <i>Dicken</i>, and <i>Deakin</i> and was easily confused with   Deacon  , of which it may also be a variant.","German: variant of   Dick  ."]},{"name":"Deakins","meanings":["English: variant of   Deacon  , with post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>.","English: variant of   Dickens  .","In some cases possibly also an Americanized form of Dutch <b>Dekens</b>: genitivized patronymic from a pet form of <i>Diederik</i> (see   Dederick  )."]},{"name":"Deane","meanings":["Irish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac an Deagánaigh</b> ‘son of the deacon’ (see   Deacon  ). In Tipperary it can be from Gaelic <b>Ó Déaghain</b> ‘descendant of the deacon’. In some other cases the surname is of English origin (see   Dean  ).","English: variant of   Dean  ."]},{"name":"Deakyne","meanings":["Probably English and Irish: variant of   Deacon  ."]}]},{"name":"Roger","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From an Old French personal name, <i>Rog(i)er</i>, of Germanic (Frankish) origin, from <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>gār</i>, <i>gēr</i> ‘spear’. This was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to Britain, replacing the native Old English form <i>Hrōðgār</i>. <i>Roger</i> was one of the most popular boys' names throughout the medieval period, but less so after the Reformation, though it has continued in regular use to the present day.  Roger, Count of Sicily  (  <i>c.</i>1031–1101 ), son of Tancred, recovered Sicily from the Arabs. His son, also called Roger, ruled Sicily as king, presiding over a court noted for its splendour and patronage of the arts."],"variants":[{"name":"Rodger","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Roger  , in part from the surname derived from the given name in the Middle Ages."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Ranulph Roger deBacon was born in 1139, in Norfolk, England, United Kingdom as the son of Rudulph de Bacon. He had at least 1 son with Matilda De flanders. He died in 1187, in Letheringsett, Norfolk, England, at the age of 48."},"et":{"1139–1187":"1139–1187","1131–1183":"1131–1183","1160–1193":"1160–1193","1105–1152":"1105–1152","1139":"1139","1105":"1105","1187":"1187","1131":"1131","1152":"1152","1183":"1183","1160":"1160","1193":"1193","Letheringsett, Norfolk, England":"Letheringsett, Norfolk, England","Baconsthorpe, Norfolk, England":"Baconsthorpe, Norfolk, England","Baconthorpe, Norfolk, England":"Norfolk, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Erpingham, Norfolk, England":"Erpingham, Norfolk, England","Normandy, France":"Normandie, Prantsusmaa"},"fi":{"1139–1187":"1139–1187","1131–1183":"1131–1183","1160–1193":"1160–1193","1105–1152":"1105–1152","1139":"1139","1105":"1105","1187":"1187","1131":"1131","1152":"1152","1183":"1183","1160"